        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2020-04-17 22:06:10.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHi,\n\nThis change aims to introduce a new data structure called `Try` to replace `Either`. As some of you mentioned it, `Either` is currently pretty confusing, with an API that is hard to read.\n\nIn contrast with `Either`, `Try` relies on exception handling and is designed to encapsulate computations resulting in an exception. The advantage compared to `Either` is that the indication of the line of code throwing the exception is preserved, which eases debugging while minimizing the stack trace. On the other hand, it also provides a higher level of composition, so it is pretty much the best of both worlds:\n```\nString unsafe() throws RuntimeException { /* ... */ }\nTry<String> safe = Try.make(() -> unsafe());\n```\nIn order to get the value resulting from a `Try`, one has to call `get`. `get` takes two callbacks, one that is called in case of success, one that is called in case of errors:\n```\nTry<String> safe = Try.make(() -> unsafe());\nsafe.consume(s -> System.out.println(s), exception -> { throw exception; })\n```\nA safer option is to provide an exception handler:\n```\nsafe.get(s -> s), exception -> { /*  handle the exception and return a fallback value */ })\n```\n`Try` could provide other interesting combinators, but before going forward, I wanted to know what you guys think about it. As of today, I have only refactored a small piece of code allowing to go from an `Either` to a `Try` and vice-versa.\n\nThank you in advance for your help and suggestions.\n\nFrancis.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
